{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"943630c2-fe03-4340-9c5e-e04508a7bf3a","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is only for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me share the standard approaches instead.\n\n### Analyzing a .NET crash dump\n\n**Option 1: `dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform)\n```bash\n# Install the tool\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Analyze the dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\nUseful commands inside the interactive session:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack of the crashing thread\n- `pe` — print the last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap overview\n- `threads` — list all threads\n- `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` — inspect other threads\n\n**Option 2: `lldb` with SOS plugin** (Linux)\n```bash\ndotnet-sos install\nlldb --core your-file.dmp\n```\n\n**Option 3: WinDbg/Visual Studio** (Windows)\nOpen the `.dmp` file directly; load SOS with `.loadby sos coreclr`.\n\n---\n\n### Quick triage checklist\n1. Run `pe` to see if there's an unhandled exception with a stack trace.\n2. Run `threads` → find the thread that faulted → `setthread` → `clrstack`.\n3. Check for `StackOverflowException` or `OutOfMemoryException` patterns.\n\nWould you like me to run `dotnet-dump analyze` on your file if you can provide the path?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e970f1c3-e69f-4d03-b6e2-650c5eeb7392","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\" So that skill is not appropriate here.\n\nI should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing their dump file.","outputTokens":478,"requestId":"F88B:DF52E:69DDD9F:73DE3A5:69FA0098"},"id":"d8802d90-dfd4-46bb-8721-ddf1a886a996","timestamp